fields.content:
Small though we are, we have something important to offer: A supportive community and a real sense of hometown.

There's something truly special about the way people take pride in their community here, and you'll see it wherever you go. It's apparent at Panthers games in Thomas Gymnasium when every seat in the auditorium is filled and the crowd is roaring, united by enthusiasm for the home team. You'll see it in the way local homeowners lovingly take care of their property, in the way people spend hours perfecting their Mardi Gras costumes, in the way people volunteer for local organizations for the purpose of strengthening the community.

In Pinckneyville, we're bound together by our love of our hometown, and that's good enough for us.
fields.headline: Community Pride
fields.caption: I'm a caption

fields.content:
Pinckneyville's excellent public and parochial education system has a simple objective: to prepare our kids for what may lie beyond their small-town roots. Small class sizes and committed faculty, staff, administrators, and board members along with strong community involvement all play a role in our community's educational success.

Our city provides residents with a wealth of opportunities for lifelong education. Pinckneyville Elementary houses over 300 students from kindergarten to fourth grade, and the Pinckneyville Junior High School has an enrollment of about 275 for grades 5-8. Community Consolidated District 204, another elementary school, offers small class sizes and plenty of one-on-one instruction from its highly experienced staff.

Established in 1887, St. Bruno Catholic School strives to provide students with good academic preparation for high school in addition to a strong moral background for life. The school has a prekindergarten through eighth grade curriculum and is open to students of all faiths.

These schools all feed into our community's single high school, where students enjoy a well-rounded education and a variety of great athletic programs. High school students can enroll in dual credit classes offered through Rend Lake College to get a head start on their college careers.

The hometown values imbued here represent a significant competitive advantage, regardless of the career or post-secondary direction our children may take.
fields.headline: Education
fields.caption: I'm a caption

fields.content:
No one's really sure how it got the name “Mardi Gras.” Pinckneyville's annual celebration in October, which dates all the way back to the 1920s, is a far cry from the traditional Fat Tuesday revelry held before Lent. But the festivities are a source of pride for the city all the same, and Pinckneyville residents look forward to our version of Mardi Gras all year round.

Each year's celebration has a theme chosen from a list of entries. Preparations for floats, costumes and activities begin weeks in advance. The Mardi Gras Scholarship Pageant is held prior to the event, and a queen is crowned to reign over the entire celebration.

On the Friday of Mardi Gras, the weekend kicks off with a kids' costume parade in the afternoon, followed by trick or treat at the fire house courtesy of the community's businesses.

On Saturday, downtown streets are blocked off and the community comes together to enjoy a flea market, craft and antique fair, car show, live entertainment, and other activities. Daytime attractions end at 4 p.m., and the annual Mardi Gras Parade begins at 7 o'clock sharp. The parade, with floats, marching bands, and a host of outrageously costumed characters from within the community, draws thousands to Pinckneyville's streets.
fields.headline: Mardi Gras
fields.caption: I'm a caption

fields.content:
We believe the old saying is true: It really does take a village to raise a child. That's why we're committed to providing kids with plenty of fun, constructive, engaging activities as they grow to adulthood in our warm community.

Youthful days here are punctuated with bike rides to the pool, fishing bluegill and bass out of the many lakes of Pyramid State Park, the pure joy of lining up on the hardwood under the basketball goals of Thomas Gymnasium after another exciting Panther victory, taking the ball-diamond as a youth or church-league softball player, and just knowing that you are part of an extended family called Pinckneyville. With good reason, our hometown's slogan is “The Friendly Little City,” and you'll find few places more friendly to, or supportive of, the young and the young at heart.

Young athletes can join the soccer or swim team, take dance classes, learn gymnastics, or even join the IHSA-sanctioned, competitive fishing club at the high school. We have a 4-H program devoted to youth empowerment and development, and the teachers at our schools are passionate about providing students with the tools to succeed.
fields.headline: Youth Activities
fields.caption: I'm a caption

fields.content:
We work hard to ensure that you can always feel safe and at ease here in Pinckneyville. The city's police department is on call for 24-hour law enforcement and emergency services, and an auxiliary police team of local citizens also plays a role in keeping our community secure.

But it's not just the local authorities that make Pinckneyville a safe place—it's the community itself. We're lucky enough to be populated by good citizens who care about making our town a better place, and their involvement has a huge hand in crime prevention.

In 2014, Pinckeyville was listed as #8 on a list of the 50 safest cities in Illinois by SafeWise. The list was based on criteria regarding property and violent crime, and it sought to highlight communities with residents and local governments making strides to maintain a safe environment. The numbers for our "Friendly Little City" were astoundingly low: We had just 1.77 violent crimes per 1,000 and 4.08 property crimes per 1,000.

Ask anybody who lives in Pinckneyville—our community's safety is one of the major perks of living here. You can't put a price on the knowledge that you, your loved ones and your property are safe and sound.
fields.headline: Safe Community
fields.caption: I'm a caption

fields.content:
There's no better place than Pinckneyville to celebrate the beauty of the Southern Illinois region. Host city to Illinois' largest state park (Pyramid), perched within a short drive of the first- and second-largest lakes in the state (Carlye Kale and Rend Lake) and situated near the edge of the vast Shawnee National Forest, our town is an outdoorsman's paradise.

The area boasts healthy populations of wild turkey and whitetail deer, and each year hunters enjoy the chance to harvest a variety of water fowl. Small game, upland game, predator hunting and trapshooting are long-standing traditions. And Pinckneyville is a great place to wet a line—the area's many reclaimed strip mining cuts, ponds, lakes and creeks are teeming with a number of different species, from largemouth bass to bluegill.

Because Pinckneyville is such a hot spot for outdoor sporting, it's no wonder that our city is home to three widely renowned gunsmiths. Mann & Son, Hicks Trading Station and Wright Inc. draw people from 100 miles away or more to check out their unique, beautifully crafted firearms.

Beyond hunting and camping, the Pinckneyville area offers a variety of water-related outdoor sports, such as sailing, motor boating, canoeing and kayaking. We also have some of the best golf to be found in Southern Illinois.
fields.headline: The Great Outdoors
fields.caption: I'm a caption

fields.content:
The American Thresherman Association moved its annual threshing show to Pinckneyville from Highland, IL, in 1962, and it's been bringing the community together ever since.

Hosted at the Perry County Fairgrounds, the festival celebrates early agriculture with a variety of sights and hands-on activities. Patrons can learn about horse-, steam- and tractor-powered plowing and milling through live demonstrations, and the draft horse pulls and mule relays are a fun source of competition. The festival, which happens twice a year in August and then in the fall, offers members of our community a chance to explore antique tractors and pieces of farming equipment, many of which are the only remaining machinery of their kind.

But the Thresherman show isn't just a place to learn about the evolution of farming technology—it serves to remind us of the culture we're born of as rural Southern Illinoisans. Seeing how generations past worked with the soil connects us to the land, and to our own heritage. That's why the show has grown into such a cultural phenomenon and a source of pride for Pinckneyville.
fields.headline: Thresherman Outdoor Festival
fields.caption: I'm a caption

fields.content:
We're a small town in rural middle America, so it stands to reason that when something needs doing, it's reminiscent of a barn-raising—everybody pitches in.

Volunteerism is a central element of life in Pinckneyville. Despite our small size, we have a wealth of organizations and events designed to help people in need and promote growth in the community.

Pinckneyville is home to a robust volunteer fire department and an auxiliary police force, both of which keep the city safe and protected. Local youth are able to get involved with volunteerism early on through school-sponsored events and Scout troops, and the Pinckneyville Chamber of Commerce frequently hosts events to give rise to positive change in the region.

The Sharing and Caring Thrift Shop is a great example of the spirit of generosity in Pinckneyville. Thanks to support from donors and the city, the volunteer-operated store is thriving in its new building and provides scholarships to PCHS students entering the health care field.

But Pinckneyville's volunteer spirit starts with neighbors helping neighbors, and it seems everyone who lives here has a story about a time the town rallied in the face of adversity. When someone gets hurt or sick or runs into some bad luck, we'll do whatever it takes to get that person back on his or her feet. That sense of interconnectedness is something you can always count on.
fields.headline: Volunteer Spirit and Generosity
fields.caption: I'm a caption

fields.content:
When you aren't well, the last thing you want is a long trip to see your doctor or an extended stay in a distant hospital. Thankfully, our community has access to big-city amenities, and that includes superior health care.

Pinckneyville Community Hospital (PCH) offers a wide range of advanced services, from rehabilitation to oncology. The hospital also hosts specialists from larger cities who hold regularly scheduled clinics in a variety of medical disciplines, giving Pinckneyville residents a hometown opportunity to see doctors with particular areas of expertise. If you're ever in need of imaging services or critical care, you won't have to go far.

September 2013 marked the ceremonial groundbreaking for the brand new, state-of-the-art PCH facility, a multi-million dollar project 11 years in the making. The new hospital will further PCH's mission to provide convenient and equal access to quality healthcare close to home.

In addition, the Pinckneyville area offers access to a myriad of non-emergency medical professionals, such as general practitioners and chiropractors. Whatever your medical needs, the trusted experts in our community have what it takes to put you on the road to good health.
fields.headline: Quality Local Healthcare
fields.caption: I'm a caption

fields.content:
The people of Pinckneyville are motivated by their beliefs to build a better community. Our residents are connected by their spirituality, and that spirituality fosters generosity, compassion and neighborliness, giving us a strong set of values we can always rely on in times of crisis.

Christianity is the most commonly practiced religion in the area, and Pinckneyville offers houses of worship for a wide variety of denominations, including Catholic, Apostolic, Assembly of God, Baptist, Lutheran, Methodist, Pentecostal and Presbyterian.

Despite the diversity of religious branches, the churches in Pinckneyville manage to work together in an interfaith way. Residents gather outside the Perry County Courthouse each year to mark the National Day of Prayer, and the town pulls together to hold memorial services for fallen soldiers when tragedy strikes. Our faith imbues our lives in Pinckneyville with meaning, and it's one of the many things that holds our community together.
fields.headline: Community of Faith
fields.caption: I'm a caption
